qas.question: In what century were sailors obligated to relocate from Plympton due to silting?
What did Sutton mean in the Old English language?
In what year was the first written reference to Plymouth made?
During whose reign was the former town of Sutton referred to as Plymouth?

context: The settlement of Plympton, further up the River Plym than the current Plymouth, was also an early trading port, but the river silted up in the early <a0_0>11th<a0_0/> century and forced the mariners and merchants to settle at the current day Barbican near the river mouth. At the time this village was called Sutton, meaning <a1_0>south town<a1_0/> in Old English. The name Plym Mouth, meaning "<a4_0>mouth of the River Plym<a4_0/>" was first mentioned in a Pipe Roll of <a2_0>1211<a2_0/>. The name Plymouth first officially replaced Sutton in a charter of <a3_0>King Henry VI<a3_0/> in 1440. See Plympton for the derivation of the name Plym.
